<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="376" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[867,1470,1917,2101]" lastBlockId="3.[230,832,285,2101]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="376" pageId="2" pageNumber="375">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[867,977,1917,1941]" pageId="2" pageNumber="375">Remarks.</emphasis>
In the Oriental, Australian and Oceanic regions, the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1055,1175,1949,1973]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1055,1175,1949,1973]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="375">Plagiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows two distinct tracks, which can be dated: one in the Miocene and the other in the Pliocene-Pleistocene (
<bibRefCitation author="MATILE, L." box="[1175,1317,2013,2037]" journalOrPublisher="Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Editions du museum, Zoologie" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" pagination="1 - 682" part="148" refId="ref4686" refString="MATILE, L. (1990): Recherches sur la systematique et l'evolution des Keroplatidae (Diptera Mycetophiloi- dea). - Memoires du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, Editions du museum, Zoologie 148: 1 - 682." title="Recherches sur la systematique et l'evolution des Keroplatidae (Diptera Mycetophiloi- dea)" type="journal article" year="1990">MATILE 1990</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1340,1421,2013,2037]" captionStart="Fig. 62" captionStartId="10.[230,265,1630,1652]" captionTargetBox="[327,1418,301,1601]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[230,1470,254,1623]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 62. Plagiodera spp., distribution area of the studied species. The dotted area represents the track Pliocene-Pleistocene (L. MATILE 1990). □ GroupA:P.aerea(Philippines);P.riparia(Sulawesi,Bali,NewGuinea,Australia:N.Territory?);P.hiekei n.sp.(NewGuinea); P.punctipennis (Philippines). ● Group B: P. chapuisi (New Guinea); P. lownei (Australia); P. nitidipennis (Australia); P.amplipennis (Australia); P. philippinensis (Philippines). * Group C: P.cheni (New Guinea,Bismarck:New Ireland); P.violaceipennis(Solomon, Fiji,Tonga);P.fulvicollis (New Hebrides, New Caledonia?); P.samoana (Samoa). M = male; F = female. Notes:The data of Tonga (P.cheni group) is taken from the catalogue of C.A.M.REID: Chrysomelinae ofAustralia, New Guinea, New Zealand, Pacific Region and relevant S EAsian Taxa. 1993, unpublished manuscript kindly provided to one of the authors (M.D.).Probably P.violaceipennisandP.fulvicollisare synonyms andP.samoanais onlyasubspecies ofthis complex.For more precise findings we need deeper studies based on much more material." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3095975/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="375">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
). As some species populate North India and Nepal (SPRECH- ER- 
<bibRefCitation author="SPRECHER- UEBERSAX, E." box="[901,1070,2077,2101]" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia et Collectiones Frey" pageId="2" pageNumber="375" pagination="375 - 512" part="33" refId="ref4893" refString="SPRECHER- UEBERSAX, E. (2011): A new catalogue of Leaf beetles (Coleoptera Chrysomelidae) from Nepal. - Entomologica Basiliensia et Collectiones Frey 33: 375 - 512." title="A new catalogue of Leaf beetles (Coleoptera Chrysomelidae) from Nepal" type="journal article" year="2011">UEBERSAX 2011</bibRefCitation>
), the temporal scale might be also old- er. Another hypothesis could be a more recent dispersal in North India and the Himalayan region from Southeast Asia. The diffusion of these species in the Pacific area might also have occurred in several successive waves. Thus, we agree with 
<bibRefCitation author="SANMARTIN, J. &amp; RONQUIST, F." box="[453,793,413,437]" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Biology" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" pagination="261 - 243" part="53" refId="ref4797" refString="SANMARTIN, J. &amp; RONQUIST, F. (2004): Southern Hemisphere Biogeography Inferred by Event-Based Models: Plant versus Animal Patterns. - Systematic Biology 53 (2): 261 - 243." title="Southern Hemisphere Biogeography Inferred by Event-Based Models: Plant versus Animal Patterns" type="journal article" year="2004">SANMARTIN &amp; RONQUIST (2004)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[230,832,285,2101]" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<taxonomicName box="[270,390,445,469]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[270,390,445,469]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Plagiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of the Oriental region and the Indochinese and Malayan subregion.
</emphasis>
The species 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. atmanama, P. cupreata, P. rufescens</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[690,831,510,533]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. yunnanica</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[237,490,541,565]" captionStart="Figs 65-76" captionStartId="11.[230,273,1989,2011]" captionText="Figs 65-76.Plagioderaspp.65-70 –P.hiekei n.sp.(65–antennaofmale,66–antennaoffemale,67–thorax,68–baseofthorax and anterior part of the elytra, schematic, 69 – aedeagus, dorsal view, 70 – aedeagus, lateral view); 71 – P.riparia JACOBY, 1885, base of thorax and anterior part of the elytra, schematic; 72-76 – P.yunnanica CHEN, 1934 (72 – antenna of male, 73 – antenna of female, 74 – aedeagus, dorsal view, 75 – aedeagus, lateral view, 76 – spermatheca). Abbreviations: EC = elytral calli, HC = humeral calli, Pr = pronotum,Sct =scutellum." pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Figs 72, 73, 74, 75, 76</figureCitation>
) are known only in the strictly limited Indochinese subregion, while in the Malayan subregion the single peculiar species 
<emphasis box="[683,796,606,629]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. riparia</emphasis>
is known, which is also widespread in Bali, Flores, Sulawesi (Celebes), Aru and West New Guinea and, to be confirmed, into the Northern Territory of Australia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[230,832,285,2101]" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<taxonomicName box="[270,390,733,757]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[270,390,733,757]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Plagiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of the Oriental region and the Papuan and Polynesian subregions.
</emphasis>
In New Guinea, all groups of 
<taxonomicName box="[392,512,797,821]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[392,512,797,821]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Plagiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
discussed in this study are present. 
<emphasis box="[328,438,830,853]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. riparia</emphasis>
belongs to species group “A” to which 
<emphasis box="[308,416,862,885]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. riparia</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Eva Sprecher- Uebersax &amp; Mauro Daccordi, 2016" authorityName="Eva Sprecher- Uebersax &amp; Mauro Daccordi" authorityYear="2016" box="[479,576,861,885]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hiekei" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[479,576,861,885]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. hiekei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[588,651,862,885]" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also belong. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. riparia</emphasis>
is known from various localities in New Guinea: Adelbert Mts., Wanuma; north-east Kepilam (2600 m); Sorong, Salawatti; Biak Island; Kampong; NE Wum; Japen Island; Kontiunai; Iba; Wamena, Ibele river valley; Balien valley; Kainantu; Jayawijaya, Wamena. The species group “B” includes species known from Australia (
<emphasis box="[351,822,1085,1109]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. lownei, P. nitidipennis, P. amplipennis</emphasis>
) as well as from the Philippines (
<emphasis box="[590,769,1117,1141]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. philippinensis</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 77-83" captionStartId="12.[230,273,2042,2064]" captionText="Figs 77-83. Plagiodera spp.77-78 – P.philippinensis DUVIVIER, 1885 (77 – aedeagus, dorsal view, 78 – lateral view); 79-82 – P. chapuisi JACOBY, 1885 (79 – habitus, 80 – aedeagus,dorsal view,from New Guinea,Fly River, 81 – aedeagus, dorsal view, from New Guinea,Normandby I, 82 – aedeagus,lateral view);83 – P.cheni LHOSTE, 1934, head, thorax." pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Figs 77, 78</figureCitation>
) and 
<emphasis box="[372,493,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. chapuisi</emphasis>
from New Guinea Fly River, Woodlark (Murua), Noemandly I, Wakaiuna (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 77-83" captionStartId="12.[230,273,2042,2064]" captionText="Figs 77-83. Plagiodera spp.77-78 – P.philippinensis DUVIVIER, 1885 (77 – aedeagus, dorsal view, 78 – lateral view); 79-82 – P. chapuisi JACOBY, 1885 (79 – habitus, 80 – aedeagus,dorsal view,from New Guinea,Fly River, 81 – aedeagus, dorsal view, from New Guinea,Normandby I, 82 – aedeagus,lateral view);83 – P.cheni LHOSTE, 1934, head, thorax." pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Figs 79, 80, 81, 82</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[321,406,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. cheni</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[421,499,1213,1237]" captionStart="Figs 77-83" captionStartId="12.[230,273,2042,2064]" captionText="Figs 77-83. Plagiodera spp.77-78 – P.philippinensis DUVIVIER, 1885 (77 – aedeagus, dorsal view, 78 – lateral view); 79-82 – P. chapuisi JACOBY, 1885 (79 – habitus, 80 – aedeagus,dorsal view,from New Guinea,Fly River, 81 – aedeagus, dorsal view, from New Guinea,Normandby I, 82 – aedeagus,lateral view);83 – P.cheni LHOSTE, 1934, head, thorax." pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Fig. 83</figureCitation>
) belongs to species group “C” together with species that have colonized some Pacific archipelagos, such as 
<emphasis box="[470,653,1277,1301]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. violaceipennis</emphasis>
in the Solomon Islands, Suva and Fiji, 
<emphasis box="[473,604,1309,1333]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. fulvicollis</emphasis>
of the New Hebrides and Samoa with 
<emphasis box="[408,531,1342,1365]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. samoana</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[230,832,285,2101]" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<taxonomicName box="[270,390,1373,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[270,390,1373,1397]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Plagiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of the Oriental region, subregion Philippines.
</emphasis>
In this subregion, there are only two species of group “A” (
<emphasis box="[387,473,1438,1461]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. aerea</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[525,687,1438,1461]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. punctipennis</emphasis>
) and a single one (
<emphasis box="[285,462,1469,1493]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. philippinensis</emphasis>
) from group “B”. In Sumbawa, J. ACHARD identified a single female specimen using an unpublished taxon name. This specimen is conserved in the collections of NMP and has been studied by one of the authors (M.D.) and might fit within the range of variation of the widespread 
<emphasis box="[535,639,1630,1653]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. riparia</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[653,831,1629,1653]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. philippinensis</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[277,442,1662,1685]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. punctipennis</emphasis>
, belonging to two different groups, both have the same coloration of entirely Spectrum Orange.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[230,832,285,2101]" lastBlockId="3.[867,1470,285,437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[230,650,1757,1781]" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">
<taxonomicName box="[230,350,1757,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[230,350,1757,1781]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Plagiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of the Australian Region.
</emphasis>
Among the four species known for the Australian region and described as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blackburn" authorityYear="1899" box="[264,433,1821,1845]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pseudoparopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,433,1821,1845]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Pseudoparopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
BLACKBURN, 1899, three belong to group “B” (
<emphasis box="[365,822,1853,1877]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. lownei, P. nitidipennis, P. amplipennis</emphasis>
) and a single one, known from the Northern Territory, Mt. Bundey, 144 m, but not yet described, to group “A”. If this undescribed species is confirmed (a single female is in the collection MDC), it would be evidence of a population in the Australian region originating from the Malayan subregion. The other species known from a few localities in Oriental Australia and attributed to group “B” would indicate a population in the evergreen tropical forests proceeding from New Guinea via Cape York. The discovery of 
<emphasis box="[1129,1263,349,373]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">P. fulvicollis</emphasis>
in New Caledonia needs confirmation. No 
<taxonomicName box="[1120,1240,381,405]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Plagiodera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="376" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1120,1240,381,405]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="376">Plagiodera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known from New Zealand.
</paragraph>
